## How to read the results

Each pair of columns isolates a single knob the recent commits have moved.

* **`default` vs `eager_leibniz`** — the Leibniz-deprioritization commit.
  A regression in `eager_leibniz` means Leibniz expansion was flooding the
  priority queue and the deprioritization paid off; a win for
  `eager_leibniz` means Leibniz still had productive work to do and the
  current cost is too steep.
* **`default` vs `pattern_paramod`** — the contribution of full higher-order
  unification in paramodulation alignment. Regressions here flag problems
  whose rewrites fall outside the Miller pattern fragment (flex variables
  not applied to distinct bound variables); `pattern_paramod` simply skips
  those positions.
* **`default` vs `no_paramod`** — the headline metric: how much
  paramodulation contributes overall. `:matching` skips any non-ground or
  non-second-order alignment, so on the first-order benchmarks here it is
  effectively "tableau + Leibniz".
* **`eager_leibniz` vs `no_paramod`** — controls the previous comparison
  by re-enabling cheap Leibniz. If `no_paramod` is still far behind, the
  remaining gap is genuinely from paramodulation; if it closes, `default`'s
  edge was largely the priority-queue ordering.

The expected pattern on these ten sections is `default ≈ eager_leibniz ≫
pattern_paramod > no_paramod` on the heavier equational problems (group
theory, Robinson, Section 10), and a much flatter spread on the trivial
chains and predicate-rewrite problems. Inversions of that pattern are
where the interesting calibration questions live.
